public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String day = "SAT";

        // Modern switch expression (Java 14+):
        String type = switch (day) {
            case "MON", "TUE", "WED", "THU", "FRI" -> "Weekday";
            case "SAT", "SUN" -> "Weekend";
            default -> "Unknown";
        };
        System.out.println(day + " is a " + type);

        // Also works with integers:
        int month = 7;
        int daysInMonth = switch (month) {
            case 1, 3, 5, 7, 8, 10, 12 -> 31;
            case 4, 6, 9, 11            -> 30;
            case 2                      -> 28;
            default -> throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid month: " + month);
        };
        System.out.println("Days in month " + month + ": " + daysInMonth);
    }
}

instruction:
For multi-statement switch cases, use `yield` to return a value:

```java
String result = switch (x) {
    case 1 -> "one";
    case 2 -> {
        System.out.println("Processing...");
        yield "two";  // yield returns from a block
    }
};
```

